H0.text: Final velocity is the effect in which, as an object falls, air resistance gradually increases until it equals the pull of gravity.

H1.text: Initial velocity is the effect in which, as an object falls, air resistance gradually increases until it equals the pull of gravity.

H2.text: Escape velocity is the effect that occurs when an object's falling air resistance gradually increases until it equals the pull of gravity.

H3.text: Terminal velocity is the effect in which, as an object falls, air resistance gradually increases until it equals the pull of gravity.

A4.text: At some speed, the drag or force of resistance will be equal to the gravitational pull on the object.
